<<
  /Author (Australian Institute of Criminology)
  /CreationDate (D:20061115092207+11'00')
  /Creator (Adobe InDesign CS2 \(4.0.1\))
  /Keywords (Computer related crime; Computer security; Computer hacking; Computer software; Computer viruses; Threat assessment)
  /ModDate (D:20070404154957+10'00')
  /Producer (Adobe PDF Library 7.0)
  /Subject ('Malware' refers to malicious software. Software is potentially malicious if it can be used to harm either the computer on which it is hosted or another computer. Software may also be considered malicious if it is designed to install itself on a computer, particularly if it does so in a way that may compromise the security of the computer. Most malicious software takes advantage of the vulnerability-exploit cycle in software development. Within the vulnerability-exploit cycle, a hacker may develop a distinct form of malicious code that is not based on other malicious code already in existence. Hacking, viruses, worms and Trojan horses all involve unauthorised access to, or modification or use of, computers or data, and these are summarised in this paper. Threat assessment is also outlined.)
  /Title (Malware : viruses, worms, Trojan horses)
  /Trapped /Unknown
>>
endobj

